[[Image:Cytochrome c.png|thumb|250px|Cytochrome ''c'' with heme ''c''.]]
'''Cytochromes''' are [[protein]]s containing [[heme]] as a [[Cofactor (biochemistry)|cofactor]]. They are classified according to the type of heme and its [[Chemical bond|mode of binding]]. Four varieties are recognized by the [[International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology|IUBMB]], cytochromes a, cytochromes b, [[Cytochrome c family|cytochromes c]] and cytochrome d.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|date=1992-01-05|title=Nomenclature Committee of the International Union of Biochemistry (NC-IUB). Nomenclature of electron-transfer proteins. Recommendations 1989.|url=http://www.jbc.org/content/267/1/665|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|language=en|volume=267|issue=1|pages=665–677|issn=0021-9258|pmid=1309757}}</ref> Cytochrome function is linked to the reversible [[redox]] change from [[ferrous]] (Fe(II)) to the [[ferric]] (Fe(III)) oxidation state of the [[iron]] found in the heme core.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Lehninger Principles of Biochemistry |last=L. |first=Lehninger, Albert |date=2000 |publisher=Worth Publishers |isbn=978-1572591530 |edition=3rd |location=New York |oclc=42619569}}</ref> In addition to the classification by the [[International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology|IUBMB]] into four cytochrome classes, several additional classifications such as [[Cytochrome c oxidase|cytochrome o]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Puustinen|first=A.|last2=Wikström|first2=M.|date=1991-07-15|title=The heme groups of cytochrome o from Escherichia coli|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=88|issue=14|pages=6122–6126|doi=10.1073/pnas.88.14.6122|issn=0027-8424|pmid=2068092|pmc=52034}}</ref> and [[cytochrome P450]] can be found in biochemical literature.
==History== Cytochromes were initially described in 1884 by [[Charles Alexander MacMunn| MacMunn]] as respiratory pigments (myohematin or histohematin).<ref name=MacMunn>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rstl.1886.0007 | jstor = 109482 | pages = 267–298 | author1 = Mac Munn, C. A | title = Researches on Myohaematin and the Histohaematins | journal = Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London | volume = 177 | year = 1886}}</ref> In the 1920s, [[David Keilin|Keilin]] rediscovered these respiratory pigments and named them the cytochromes, or “cellular pigments”.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Keilin|first=D.|date=1925-08-01|title=On cytochrome, a respiratory pigment, common to animals, yeast, and higher plants|journal=Proc. R. Soc. Lond. B|language=en|volume=98|issue=690|pages=312–339|doi=10.1098/rspb.1925.0039|issn=0950-1193}}</ref> He classified these heme proteins on the basis of the position of their lowest [[Ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy|energy absorption band]] in their reduced state, as cytochromes ''a'' (605&nbsp;nm), ''b'' (≈565&nbsp;nm), and ''c'' (550&nbsp;nm). The ultra-violet (UV) to visible spectroscopic signatures of hemes are still used to identify heme type from the reduced bis-pyridine-ligated state, i.e., the pyridine hemochrome method. Within each class, cytochrome ''a'', ''b'', or ''c'', early cytochromes are numbered consecutively, e.g. cyt ''c'', cyt ''c<sub>1</sub>'', and cyt ''c<sub>2</sub>'', with more recent examples designated by their reduced state R-band maximum, e.g. cyt ''c<sub>559</sub>''.<ref name="pmid14871137">{{cite journal |author1=Reedy, C. J. |author2=Gibney, B. R. | title = Heme protein assemblies | journal = Chem Rev | volume = 104 | issue = 2 | pages = 617–49 |date=February 2004 | pmid = 14871137 | doi = 10.1021/cr0206115 | url = }}</ref>
==Structure and function== The [[heme]] group is a highly conjugated ring system (which allows its [[electron]]s to be very mobile) surrounding an iron ion. The iron in cytochromes usually exists in a ferrous (Fe<sup>2+</sup>) and a ferric (Fe<sup>3+</sup>) state with a ferroxo (Fe<sup>4+</sup>) state found in catalytic intermediates.<ref name=":0" /> Cytochromes are, thus, capable of performing [[Electron transport chain|electron transfer reactions]] and [[catalysis]] by reduction or oxidation of their heme iron. The cellular location of cytochromes depends on their function. They can be found as [[globular protein]]s and [[membrane protein]]s.
In the process of [[dioxidative phosphorylation]], a globular [[Cytochrome c|cytochrome cc protein]] is involved in the electron transfer from the membrane-bound [[Coenzyme Q – cytochrome c reductase|complex III]] to [[Cytochrome c oxidase|complex IV]]. Complex II itself is composed of several subunits, one of which is a b-type cytochrome while another one is a c-type cytochrome. Both domains are involved in electron transfer within the complex. Complex IV contains a cytochrome a/a3-domain that transfers electrons and catalyzes the reaction of [[oxygen]] to water. Photosystem II, the first [[protein complex]] in the [[light-dependent reactions]] of oxygenic [[photosynthesis]], contains a cytochrome b subunit. [[Prostaglandin-endoperoxide synthase 2|Cyclooxygenase 2]], an enzyme involved in [[inflammation]], is a cytochrome b protein.
In the early 1960s, a linear [[Molecular evolution|evolution]] of cytochromes was suggested by [[Emanuel Margoliash]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Margoliash|first=E.|date=1963|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=50|issue=4|pages=672–679|issn=0027-8424|pmc=221244|pmid=14077496|doi=10.1073/pnas.50.4.672|title=Primary Structure and Evolution of Cytochrome C}}</ref> that led to the [[molecular clock]] hypothesis. The apparently constant evolution rate of cytochromes can be a helpful tool in trying to determine when various organisms may have diverged from a [[Common descent|common ancestor]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kumar|first=Sudhir|date=2005|title=Molecular clocks: four decades of evolution|journal=Nature Reviews. Genetics|volume=6|issue=8|pages=654–662|doi=10.1038/nrg1659|issn=1471-0056|pmid=16136655}}</ref>
==Types== Several kinds of cytochrome exist and can be distinguished by [[spectroscopy]], exact structure of the heme group, inhibitor sensitivity, and reduction potential.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://intranet.tdmu.edu.ua/data/kafedra/internal/chemistry/classes_stud/en/med/lik/ptn/2/03.%20Investigation%20of%20biological%20oxidation,%20oxidative%20phosphorylation.htm|title=Investigation of biological oxidation, oxidative phosphorylation and ATP synthesis. Inhibitor and Uncouplers of oxidative phosphorylation.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>
Four types of cytochromes are distinguished by their prosthetic groups:
{| class="wikitable" ! Type !! Prosthetic group |- | [[Cytochrome a]] || [[heme A]] |- | [[Cytochrome b]] || [[heme B]] |- |[[Cytochrome c family|Cytochrome c]] |[[heme C]] ([[Covalent bond|covalently bound]] heme b)<ref>{{MeshName|Cytochrome+c+Group}}.</ref> |- | [[Cytochrome d]] || [[heme D]] (Heme B with γ-spirolactone)<ref name="pmid8621527">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1074/jbc.271.15.8863 | last1 = Murshudov | first1 = G. | last2 = Grebenko | first2 = A. | last3 = Barynin | first3 = V. | last4 = Dauter | first4 = Z. | last5 = Wilson | first5 = K. | last6 = Vainshtein | first6 = B. | last7 = Melik-Adamyan | first7 = W. | last8 = Bravo | first8 = J. | last9 = Ferrán | first9 = J. | last10 = Ferrer | first10 = J. C. | last11 = Switala | first11 = J. | last12 = Loewen | first12 = P. C. | last13 = Fita | first13 = I. | title = Structure of the heme ''d'' of ''Penicillium vitale'' and ''Escherichia coli'' catalases | journal = The Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 271 | issue = 15 | pages = 8863–8868 | year = 1996 | pmid = 8621527 }}</ref> |}
There is no "cytochrome e," but [[cytochrome f]], found in the [[Cytochrome b6f complex|cytochrome b<sub>6</sub>f complex]] of plants is a c-type cytochrome.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bendall |first=Derek S. |date=2004 |title=The Unfinished Story of Cytochrome f |journal=Photosynthesis Research |language=en |volume=80 |issue=1–3 |pages=265–276 |doi=10.1023/b:pres.0000030454.23940.f9 |issn=0166-8595 |pmid=16328825}}</ref>
In [[mitochondrion|mitochondria]] and [[chloroplast]]s, these cytochromes are often combined in [[Electron transfer chain|electron transport]] and related metabolic pathways:<ref>{{cite book |last=Doidge |first=Norman |date=2015 |title=The brain's way of healing : remarkable discoveries and recoveries from the frontiers of neuroplasticity |publisher=Penguin Group |page=173 |isbn=978-0-698-19143-3 }}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" ! Cytochromes !! Combination |- | ''a'' and ''a<sub>3</sub>'' || [[Cytochrome c oxidase]] ("Complex IV") with electrons delivered to complex by soluble [[cytochrome c]] (hence the name) |- | ''b'' and ''[[Cytochrome C1|c<sub>1</sub>]]'' || [[Coenzyme Q - cytochrome c reductase]] ("Complex III") |- | ''b<sub>6</sub>'' and ''[[Cytochrome f|f]]'' || [[Plastoquinol—plastocyanin reductase]] |}
A distinct family of cytochromes is the [[cytochrome P450]] family, so named for the characteristic [[Soret peak]] formed by absorbance of light at wavelengths near 450&nbsp;nm when the heme iron is reduced (with [[sodium dithionite]]) and complexed to [[carbon monoxide]]. These enzymes are primarily involved in [[steroidogenesis]] and [[detoxification]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Miller|first=Walter L.|title=Disorders in the Initial Steps in Steroidogenesis|date=2014|work=Genetic Steroid Disorders|pages=145–164|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9780124160064|last2=Gucev|first2=Zoran S.|doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-416006-4.00011-9}}</ref><ref name=":1" />
